# {{.Name}} — Agent & Developer Guide

## What this is

{{.Name}} is a service scaffolded by devedge. It runs on the devedge substrate, which handles
local Kubernetes routing, TLS termination, database provisioning, and the development lifecycle
commands. Authorization is governed by `(infoblox.authz.v1.rule)` proto annotations: every RPC
declares its required permission in the proto file, and the server enforces this fail-closed at
boot — an RPC without a rule (or explicit `public: true`) will refuse to start. That is
intentional and not a bug to work around.

## Layout

- `devedge.yaml` — substrate contract: hostname, port, dependencies, migration path. Keep it authoritative.
- `proto/{{.ProtoPkg}}/v1/` — **the source of truth** for the API and authz rules. Edit here first.
- `third_party/proto/` — codegen inputs only. Never edit by hand.
- `internal/gen/` — generated by `de generate`. Never edit by hand; changes will be overwritten.
- `internal/server/` — RPC handler implementations. Business logic lives here.
- `internal/store/` — Postgres-backed storage layer (pgx).
- `db/migrations/` — SQL migration files (numbered, up/down pairs).
- `cmd/{{.Name}}/` — binary entrypoint.

> Gotcha: the generated gateway function `Register...HandlerFromEndpoint` keeps its
> `FromEndpoint` suffix — that means "from a gRPC endpoint address", not your resource.
> Rename only the service part of the name (`RegisterNotesHandlerFromEndpoint`).


## Renaming the example resource

The scaffold ships a `WebhookEndpoint` resource as a concrete, working example. To replace it
with your own resource:

1. Rename `proto/{{.ProtoPkg}}/v1/webhook_endpoint.proto` to match your resource name.
2. Inside that file, rename the message, service, and all RPC names.
   Every RPC **must** carry an `(infoblox.authz.v1.rule)` option (or `public: true`).
3. Update `db/migrations/0001_*.sql` to reflect your table and columns.
4. Update `internal/server/server.go` and `internal/store/store.go` to use the new type names.
5. Run `de generate` to regenerate `internal/gen/`.
6. Run `de test` — all tests must pass before proceeding.

## The development loop

```
de generate            # regenerate internal/gen from proto sources (buf + pinned plugins)
de project up          # provision db, apply migrations, start routing
make run               # build + run the binary; it listens on :8080 (make run delegates go run)

# Example CRUD call (HTTP/JSON via grpc-gateway). The edge routes {{.APIPath}}
# on {{.Host}} to this service and strips the prefix, so the public URL is
# {{.Layout}} while the service keeps serving /v1/...:
curl -s -X POST https://{{.Host}}{{.APIPath}}/v1/webhook-endpoints \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -H "Grpc-Metadata-x-dev-subject: dev" \
  -d '{"endpoint": {"url": "https://receiver.example.com/hook", "secret": "s3cr3t", "event_filters": ["push"]}}'
```

The `Grpc-Metadata-x-dev-subject: dev` header identifies the caller to the dev-only authorizer.
The subject `dev` is pre-granted all permissions; any other subject will be denied. This
authorizer is a development stand-in and is replaced by configuration in real deployments — do
not rely on its behavior in production code.

```
de project up --deploy  # build image + deploy to local cluster (smoke-test the container)
de project down         # tear down the dev environment
```

## Guardrails

- **Never edit `internal/gen/` or `third_party/` by hand.** They are overwritten on every
  `de generate`. Put logic in `internal/server/` and `internal/store/`.
- **Never log secrets or return them in List/Get responses** in real resources. The `secret`
  field on `WebhookEndpoint` is a teaching prop that forces you to confront secret-field
  handling from day one. In production resources, mask or omit sensitive fields.
- **`devedge.yaml` is authoritative** for hostname, port, dependencies, and the migration
  directory. Keep it in sync with any structural changes.
- **Every new RPC needs an authz rule.** The server will refuse to boot if any registered RPC
  lacks either an `(infoblox.authz.v1.rule)` option or `public: true`. This is the fail-closed
  guarantee — it is intentional.
